      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The Good",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "heading",
        "tag": "h3",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The developers wanted to hit a specific aesthetic with ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Quest for Infamy",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " and I’m happy to inform you that they hit it very well. The graphics, audio design, environments, puzzle design and more all scream the classic Sierra feel that the developers aimed to achieve. Fans nostalgic for that type of game will feel right at home at the helm. The developers even included a digital instruction manual at the beginning of the game to further their commitment to this aesthetic. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "html",
        "html": "<a href=\"https://powera.pxf.io/c/3324894/1309898/15385\" target=\"_top\" id=\"1309898\"><img src=\"//a.impactradius-go.com/display-ad/15385-1309898\" border=\"0\" alt=\"\" width=\"728\" height=\"90\"/></a><img height=\"0\" width=\"0\" src=\"https://imp.pxf.io/i/3324894/1309898/15385\" style=\"position:absolute;visibility:hidden;\" border=\"0\" />"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Quest for Infamy",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " also boasts a very high amount of player agency. Right at the outset, the player is asked to decide pretty much the entirety of how they’ll interact with it through one of three paths. The Path of the Brigand will have the player take a more brute force approach, The Path of the Rogue focuses on a more subtle and stealthy touch and finally, The Path of the Sorcerer shows a more mystical side of the game. This choice is pivotal to how you approach puzzles and combat and is felt throughout most of the game. ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 1,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "TL;DR",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
